# Router

### Note:
I solved all the subtasks that this homework includes, the forwarding process, the efficient lpm, the arp and the icmp

#### Efficient lpm

For this part of the homework I used a data structure known as a trie, as you suggested in the task description. A trie is a binary tree,
where every node has 2 sons which hold the values 1 and 0. My node structure has the field node *children[2] which holds 2 pointers to the
next nodes, and also a field called entry of type struct route_table_entry, this is only for the leaves of the trie, each leaf will hold
the ip address formed with the bits from the root, on that specific path to the leaf,
- *alloc_node* is a function that initializes a node
- *insert_node* is a function that inserts a node in the trie, note that this functions take the bits from the most significant bit to the
least significant one because my address is in little endian and I want my trie to save them in big endian. The function takes as
parameters the router entry, as well as the prefix of the ip address it can forward to and its mask.
- *init_trie* is the function which build the trie based on the route_table file, simply iterating through the table and for each entry
we apply the insert_node function with the specific parameters
- *search_ip* is the efficient function that searches through the trie and finds a match with the ip given as a parameter. The process of 
iterating through the bits of the ip address and extracting the bit value from the ip adress is similar to the insert_node. Each time we
go deeper in the trie, we are following the value of the current bit (bit_val), and current goes to the next pointer in the trie.
In the end we have a match if the entry field from our node is != NULL, because this means we hit a leaf.

#### Arp 

The Arp logic is the follwoing: first time the router receives a packet it verifies if the ether type of the ether header is of type arp.
In this case I need to do 2 more verifications because the router could either receive an arp request or an arp reply.

In the case of receiving an arp reply, I have to parse the reply (using the parse_arp_reply function) and then I must extract a packet from the queue 
and try to send it, after I make the required modifications to the packet (mainly I have to modify the ethernet destination mac), I send it to the
next closest router. If after the parsing of the arp reply and extracting the packet from the queue, I still dont find a mac address match 
in the arp table, I add the packet back to the queue (Im not sure if this scenario is possible in this homework, I havent tested that tbh).

In the case of receiving an arp request, I simply reverse the arp packet header and ethertnet header source mac addresses and destination mac addresses,
and also the target and the source ip addresses for the arp header, and send it back to the interface where it came from (if h0 sends an arp request
to r0 it must always come back on the same interface).

I send arp requests only when I dont find an arp table entry of the next hop where I want my packet to be forwarded to. For this step I use the
*generate_arp_request* and *send_arp_packet* functions;

#### The forwarding logic - IPv4

If the packet received by the router is an IPv4 packet, in the while(1) we will arrive at the else branch of the first if which verifies if the packet 
is an arp one, presented above. In this case we know we have an IPv4 packet which needs to be forwarded. First of all I have to verify if the checksum
is correct otherwise I have received a modified packet compared to the original. If the verification passes I search the closest router entry
with the search_ip function. Next I need the mac address of the next hop, if I cant find it, I add the packet to the queue and send an arp request
presented in the arp section.
If I find the mac address of next hop, I modify the ethernet header source and destination mac addresses and send the packet.

#### ICMP

For this part I have implemented the *handle_icmp_cases* function which handles the 3 cases of the icmp presented in this homework:
- destination unreachable is closest router is null;
- time exceed if ttl <= 1;
- the echo reply which the router sends to itself.

I have implemented the *generate_icmp_message* and *send_icmp_packet* functions for the actual sending part; generate_icmp_message
will return the content of the icmp message as a char buffer and send_icmp_packet will create the ether header and the ip header
over the message so that it becomes an actual packet which can be send.



